answers.body_markdown:
use `android:src` instead of `tools:srcCompat`  `tools` is your Design View in android Studio.

    &lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;utf-8&quot;?&gt;
    &lt;android.support.constraint.ConstraintLayout
        xmlns:android=&quot;http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android&quot;
        xmlns:app=&quot;http://schemas.android.com/apk/res-auto&quot;
        xmlns:tools=&quot;http://schemas.android.com/tools&quot;
        android:layout_width=&quot;match_parent&quot;
        android:layout_height=&quot;match_parent&quot;&gt;
    
    
         &lt;ImageView
                android:id=&quot;@+id/gp_tos_1&quot;
                android:layout_width=&quot;0dp&quot;
                android:layout_height=&quot;0dp&quot;
                android:layout_marginStart=&quot;16dp&quot;
                android:layout_marginTop=&quot;16dp&quot;
                android:layout_marginEnd=&quot;16dp&quot;
                app:layout_constraintDimensionRatio=&quot;h,16:9&quot;
                app:layout_constraintEnd_toEndOf=&quot;parent&quot;
                app:layout_constraintStart_toStartOf=&quot;parent&quot;
                app:layout_constraintTop_toTopOf=&quot;parent&quot;
                android:src=&quot;@drawable/berlaar&quot; /&gt;
    
    &lt;/android.support.constraint.ConstraintLayout&gt;

You should use the `app` namespace i.e **app:srcCompat=&quot;@drawable/berlaar&quot;**.

Using the `tools` namespace **tools:srcCompat=&quot;@drawable/berlaar&quot;**, the image would only show up in the preview section as its function is to help you see what you&#39;re building. 
When you hit the compile button, the image marked with `tools` namespace doesn&#39;t get into your final build and that&#39;s why you can&#39;t see any image.

You should have:

    &lt;ImageView
        android:id=&quot;@+id/gp_tos_1&quot;
        android:layout_width=&quot;0dp&quot;
        android:layout_height=&quot;0dp&quot;
        android:layout_marginStart=&quot;16dp&quot;
        android:layout_marginTop=&quot;16dp&quot;
        android:layout_marginEnd=&quot;16dp&quot;
        app:layout_constraintDimensionRatio=&quot;h,16:9&quot;
        app:layout_constraintEnd_toEndOf=&quot;parent&quot;
        app:layout_constraintStart_toStartOf=&quot;parent&quot;
        app:layout_constraintTop_toTopOf=&quot;parent&quot;
        app:srcCompat=&quot;@drawable/berlaar&quot;
        tools:srcCompat=&quot;@drawable/berlaar&quot; /&gt;

If &quot;berlaar&quot; is a vector drawable, you need to add `vectorDrawables.useSupportLibrary = true` to your app&#39;s `build.gradle` file: 

    android {
      ...
      defaultConfig {
      ...  
       vectorDrawables.useSupportLibrary = true 
     }  
    }

Usually, when this problem occurs, it&#39;s always because of one of the following reasons:

 - The image you&#39;re trying to load into the ImageView is too large.
 - The image you are trying to load into the ImageView is not a .png image.

&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;Image is too large&lt;/h1&gt;

If you are loading the image locally, a quick fix would be to put your image inside *drawable-nodpi* subfolder in the *res* folder.

You can also optimize your ImageViews to load large images by adding this to the application element of your manifest:

    android:hardwareAccelerated=&quot;false&quot;
    android:largeHeap=&quot;true&quot;

&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;Image is not a .png image&lt;/h1&gt;
No doubt, the best-performing image format is .png. But sometimes, we are faced with situations where we have to display a non-png image which are statistically known to render poorly (or not render at all). In this case, the best option is to use an image caching library like [Picasso](https://github.com/square/picasso), [Glide](https://github.com/bumptech/glide) or [Fresco](https://github.com/facebook/fresco).

&lt;br /&gt;
I hope this helps. Merry coding!

